In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Created");
    window.Activated  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Activated");
    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Deactivated");
    window.Stopped    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Stopped");
    window.Resumed    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Resumed");
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Destroying");

    // iOS / Mac Catalyst only
    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Backgrounding");

    return window;
}
```

**Event flow by platform:**

| Transition | Android | iOS / Mac Catalyst | Windows |
|---|---|---|---|
| App launch | Created → Activated | Created → Activated | Created → Activated |
| Sent to background | Deactivated → Stopped | Deactivated → Backgrounding → Stopped | Deactivated |
| Returned to foreground | Resumed → Activated | Stopped → Resumed → Activated | Activated |
| App closed | Stopped → Destroying | Stopped → Destroying | Deactivated → Destroying |

> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` fires only on iOS/Mac Catalyst (use it to save state). On Android/Windows it's never raised — use `Stopped` or `Deactivated` instead.
